The start of a new crisis-era
France and the rest of Europe, the focus of investors.
On Tuesday brauste a statistical storm by Europe.
The Member States published their claims on their GDP for the third quarter.
The Czech economy stagnated compared to the Vorquartal, Germany and France, too.
The bonds market demolishes today but all the records.
Keep investors not only Greece but now Spain, France, Austria and other countries.
The statistical office of the Euro zone, Germany, the Czech Republic and a number of other European countries published its preliminary forecasts of economic growth in the third quarter.
Germany's GDP grew by 0.5% expected by France by 0.4%.
Both countries corrected their data for the second quarter in which Germany recorded a higher growth than initially expected (growth was predicted by 0.3% 0.1%), while France a slight drop of 0.1% admitted (initial indications spoke only of stagnation).
The Czech economy grew in the third quarter of this year compared with last year by 1.5 per cent.
Vorquartal stagnated compared to gross domestic product, however, and according to Tsch. Statistical office confirmed that the trend of growth slowdown in economic performance.
The results were worse than the forecasts of analysts.
The main events:
The Czech economy grew in the third quarter of this year compared to last year by 1.5%, compared to the previous quarter, however, it has stagnated.
Preliminary and seasonal on judged according to the German economy grew by 0.5% in the third quarter.
Throughout the euro area and in the EU, the economy between July and September compared with the previous quarter growth by 0.2 per cent, which is in line with the expectations of analysts.
The Greek economy shrank by 5.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
The return on their 10-year government bonds reached the value of 28.45%.
The yield on Italian and Spanish government bonds rose up to their critical.
Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium and other countries start to feel problems...
The yield on Czech government bonds are under 4%, even if the situation in the region deteriorated.
In Germany, voices the ECB should be the lender of last resort.
