On a personal level of mass slaughter
Peter Englunds begins sensitive and generous new book "beauty and horror: A History of the First World War, told in nineteen Schicksalen" with a long list of key personnel, a heart.
Here a typing of proceeding: Are you this side carefully and make it to your read signs.
They are these people in Englunds romanhafter narrative know each other very well, and the main people than your GPS function as a beacon in these few moments where you like Englunds men and women lost in the fog of war and your illusions.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, the Nobel Prize for literature.
He has written an unusual book that he not incorrect as "a work of anti-history".
It contains only a few big names, important contracts or famous battles. There is little ambassadors, reckless reporters or discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is less a book about what happened, he said, but rather "a book about how it was." It is about "feelings, ideas, experiences and feelings."
"Beauty and horror" almost the war experience of 20 more or less unauffälligen men and women on both sides of the war of schoolgirls and Botanikern to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and office workers.
Some of these people are heroes.
Some will become prisoners of war, losing limb, crazy or die.
Each of these lives on as the Votivkerzen future has come in a church, some are added, while other lapse.
Englunds book deviates from the usual history books.
It also corrected the notion that the First World War was just the disastrous position war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and horror" ends with experts view on other war theaters: The Alps, the Balkans, the Ostfront, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are bees baskets, celebrates Christmas under the pyramids in Egypt, Tsetsefliegen are an intractable problem.
This is almost from the beginning, a very moving book.
The war swamped the lives of these people as a natural disaster such as a hurricane Katrina, after Kordit smell.
Imagine you are a woman who is at home with their children, and cannon fire in the distance. You stay or take the flight?
Who is at all?
Hardly anyone understands what happened or why this war is being fought.
"Lack of facts," Englund is, "with suspicion, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams and nightmares and rumours aufgemöbelt."
"Beauty and horror" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard stamp, a young German ship sailors.
