Climatic adversity bremsten the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez in government, rose in Sinaloa unemployment and undeclared work, while the foreign investment decreased and the economy stagnated.
2011 is in economic history Sinaloas remembered, it is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, the self-described as the initiator of change and high hopes on the economic growth fueled by the government, but as a result of the climatic adversity can be no question of growth, but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of dollars in losses in agriculture, but were in addition to the growth of the state economy close borders and in the first quarter year caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 per cent This is mainly on the historic dismantling of agricultural development at 31.16 per cent, which bremsend impact on other sectors of the economy.
According to one of the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable ("Go. Mexico's Council for sustainable agricultural development) report on the impact of the Frosts were 582,000 hectares of agricultural land damaged what 78.03 percent completely and the remaining 21.07% partially destroyed. Affected mainly the vegetable, maize and chickpeas cultivation.
The decline in economic activity until November, in the Mexican state unemployment continues to rise and the Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed during the first quarter of a rapid rise in unemployment, because from January to March had 55,053 inhabitants Sinaloas no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to and 5.28% between July and September at 6.19% to 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa. These are 18,969 people more than in the first quarter of the year.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is based on several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the School of Economic and Social Sciences at the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments, the policy of public institutions declare indirectly the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing is a rise in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including loss of liquidity in the market as a result of the cuts through the legislation to combat money laundering in Congress was adopted, because those who amass $banned way, it is not easy for them to work to invest or to use for anything," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the increase in unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people in the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, left, is decreased. This is due to the entry problems on the one hand, and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work. These people here and stay here looking for work, with high unemployment," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, given the high proportion of undeclared work. This includes according to INEGI 60.38 percent of employees who work in the country without into the coffers of the social security will be paid.
About unemployment and undeclared work, the low wages, the lowest throughout Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institution) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Intergovernmental Authority for work and social care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa, until September 5352 pesos; it is much less than the overall national average of 7375 pesos.
Decline in FDI
In addition to the reduction of economic activity and rising unemployment will be in 2011, the sharpest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last ten years, according to the Secretaría de Economía (state authority), FDI from January to June 630,597 dollars, a loss of 87.74% compared to the 5,143,312 dollars in the same period in the previous year.
The Secretaría del Gobierno de Desarrollo Económico (Intergovernmental Authority for economic development), recorded a total investment of EUR 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, above all by companies from the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the face of the economic crisis for the provincial government in July at the National Congress a loan of EUR 3,000,000,000 pesos to the reactivation of the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 communities should be invested. The country Congress approved an amount of EUR 200,600,000 pesos, until November, but had no positive effects of debt in any of the industries in the country.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first government year Mario López Valdés government incompetence.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (GOVERNMENT chamber of the manufacturing industry in Mexico) argued that in 2011, no effort to harmonize the views of the different sectors, including the provincial government, have been made.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa this year was very poor. It must work hard to regain lost ground this year and in 2012, we must be doubly hard. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well collide eingestimmte government teams have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events, such as the frost at the beginning of the year, the economy slowed more difficult and development of the country.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the Frosts. One of the main impact is a slower economy in movement is not sufficient to produce an economic dynamism, an acceptable flow of processes, products and services could produce, so this year we will finish well below our expectations," he said.
Redefine appeal
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the feed Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexico's Sinaloa) in employers' association, said the state should be more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that has been done and we believe that it is necessary for a long-term programme to redefine the economic appeal and line of the country, because it is important all the material and human resources to activate Sinaloas," he said.
There is much to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed how important it is to develop a future that the efforts of the government to better track.
"In general, I would say that the government in various areas has achieved good results. The economic development is progressing, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current government is making progress in the government.
"There are areas in which we can say that the government has acted more. What I can say is that it was done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work lies ahead of it," he said.
